[{"id":"VR856264","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<div><div class=\"stimulus_reference\"><div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure shows a diagram consisting of, from left to right along a horizontal line, an object pointing upward at point P, point uppercase F, an object pointing upward at point Q, and a convex lens. The distance between point P and the lens is three halves lowercase f. The distance between point Q and the lens is one half lowercase f. A ray is drawn from point F, slants upward and to the right, through the top of the object at point Q, and intersects the lens. The portion of the ray between point F and point Q is dashed. To the right of the lens, the ray becomes horizontal. A ray is drawn from the top of the object at point Q, slants downward and to the right, intersects the lens through its center at the horizontal line. To the right of the lens, the ray continues slanting downward and to the right at the same slope as to the left of the lens.\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/578/VR856264.g01.svg\"/></div></div></div><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">An object can be placed on the principal axis of a lens at either of two points, Point <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"P\"><math alttext=\"P\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mtext>P</mtext></math></span></span> or Point <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"Q\"><math alttext=\"Q\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mtext>Q</mtext></math></span></span>, as shown in the figure. The lens is convex with a focal length equal to <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"lowercase f\"><math alttext=\"lowercase f\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>f</mi></math></span></span>. Points <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"P\"><math alttext=\"P\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mtext>P</mtext></math></span></span>, <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"uppercase F\"><math alttext=\"uppercase F\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">F</mi></math></span></span>, and <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"Q\"><math alttext=\"Q\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mtext>Q</mtext></math></span></span> are located at distances of <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"three halves lowercase f\"><math alttext=\"three halves lowercase f\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mfrac><mn>3</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mi>f</mi></math></span></span>, <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"lowercase f\"><math alttext=\"lowercase f\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>f</mi></math></span></span>, and <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"one half lowercase f\"><math alttext=\"one half lowercase f\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mi>f</mi></math></span></span>, respectively, from the center of the lens. Additionally, two principal rays are indicated for when the object is at Point <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"Q\"><math alttext=\"Q\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mtext>Q</mtext></math></span></span>. How does the <span class=\"formatted_text text_decoration:underline\">magnitude </span>of the height of the image formed by the lens compare when the object is at Point <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"P\"><math alttext=\"P\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mtext>P</mtext></math></span></span> versus when the object is at Point <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"Q\"><math alttext=\"Q\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mtext>Q</mtext></math></span></span>? What evidence or reasoning helps support the claim?</p>\n","rubricRef":"VR856264_rubric","choicesHtml":["<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">It is greater when the object is at Point <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"Q\"><math alttext=\"Q\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mtext>Q</mtext></math></span></span>. The reciprocal of the object-lens distance <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"open parenthesis, the fraction 1 over s sub o, close parenthesis\"><math alttext=\"open parenthesis, the fraction 1 over s sub o, close parenthesis\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mo>(</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msub><mi>s</mi><mi>o</mi></msub></mfrac><mo>)</mo></math></span></span> is greater the closer the object is to the lens.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">It is greater when the object is at Point <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"Q\"><math alttext=\"Q\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mtext>Q</mtext></math></span></span>. The principal ray passing through the center of the lens makes a greater angle from the principal axis when the object is at Point <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"Q\"><math alttext=\"Q\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mtext>Q</mtext></math></span></span>.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">It is the same for both object locations. Magnification is a property of the lens and is independent of where an object is located.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">It is the same for both object locations. The principal ray originating from Point <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"uppercase F\"><math alttext=\"uppercase F\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">F</mi></math></span></span> reaches the lens at the same distance from the principal axis when the object is at either location.</p>"],"answer":3}]